==English==

===Etymology===
Named after Arius; a priest in Alexandria [[circa]] 323 CE.

===Proper noun===
'''Arian Heresy'''
# An early Christian heresy <!-- This is encyclopaedic, and needs to be refined to better define "Arian Heresy", and not just talk about Arius : # Arius reasoned that if [[Christ]] was the son of [[God]], He must be younger than God, and therefore lesser than God. Since God was [[eternal]] and Christ was not; therefore Christ was not wholly God. The [[heresy]] was --> [[scotch]]ed at the [[Council of Nicea]] in 325.

===Reference===
R C H Davis. A History of Medieval Europe. 2nd Edition. Longman 1970. Pages 16 -19.

